    <string name="about_text">

        About the Green Food Challenge \n
        As Canadians, we often think of ourselves as surrounded by nature and thoughtful about
        the environment. Indeed, Vancouver has spearheaded the Greenest City Action Plan since
        2011, with the goal of becoming the greenest city in the world by 2020.1 Of the plan’s 10
        specific goals, and one of the goals is for a ​lighter footprint,​ reducing Vancouver\'s carbon
        footprint by 33% over 2006 levels.\n\n

        -About Carbon Emissions-\n
        Greenhouse gasses are known to directly contribute to climate change,
        they are measured in C02e (Carbon dioxide equivalents). In 2015 emissions in metro Vancouver
        were about 15 million tonnes, with the avg person using about 6-8 tonnes. By 2050 we need
        emissions to be reduced to 2 tonnes per person. 1 ton is aprox 907 kg and 1kg of beef
        produces about 27kg of C02e
        \n\n

        -What Can We Do?-\n
        Outside of taking transit we can change our diet. Turns out certain food produce more C02e than
        others with lamb and Beef being the top 2 items that increase C02e. Eating less beef and
        replacing it with other kinds of meat such as fish, pork or chicken would help. And increasing
        the number of vegetables we consume would help a lot.

    </string>
